Abstract Classes

Abstract classes serve as base classes that cannot be instantiated directly. They may contain abstract methods that subclasses must implement.

### Abstract Class Syntax

```typescript
abstract class Animal {
  constructor(public name: string) {}

  // Abstract method (no implementation)
  abstract makeSound(): void;

  // Concrete method (has implementation)
  move(distance: number): void {
    console.log(`${this.name} moved ${distance}m`);
  }
}

// Cannot instantiate abstract class
// const animal = new Animal("Generic"); // Error
```

### Subclass Implementation

```typescript
class Dog extends Animal {
  makeSound(): void {
    console.log("Woof!");
  }
}

class Cat extends Animal {
  makeSound(): void {
    console.log("Meow!");
  }
}

const dog = new Dog("Buddy");
dog.makeSound(); // Woof!
dog.move(10); // Buddy moved 10m
```

### Abstract Properties

```typescript
abstract class Shape {
  abstract readonly name: string;
  abstract getArea(): number;
}

class Circle extends Shape {
  readonly name = "Circle";

  constructor(private radius: number) {
    super();
  }

  getArea(): number {
    return Math.PI * this.radius ** 2;
  }
}
```

### Abstract vs Interface

| Feature | Abstract Class | Interface |
|---------|---------------|-----------|
| Instantiation | Cannot instantiate | Cannot instantiate |
| Implementation | Can have concrete methods | No implementation |
| Constructor | Yes | No |
| Access modifiers | Yes | No |
| Multiple inheritance | No (single extends) | Yes (multiple implements) |

> **Key Point:** Use abstract classes when base classes share implementation logic; use interfaces for pure contracts.

codeExample:
abstract class Database {
  abstract connect(): void;
  abstract disconnect(): void;

  executeQuery(sql: string): void {
    this.connect();
    console.log(`Executing: ${sql}`);
    this.disconnect();
  }
}

class MySQLDatabase extends Database {
  connect(): void {
    console.log("Connected to MySQL");
  }

  disconnect(): void {
    console.log("Disconnected from MySQL");
  }
}

class PostgreSQLDatabase extends Database {
  connect(): void {
    console.log("Connected to PostgreSQL");
  }

  disconnect(): void {
    console.log("Disconnected from PostgreSQL");
  }
}

const db: Database = new MySQLDatabase();
db.executeQuery("SELECT * FROM users");
